---
// melatonin gummies — CONTEXT page (CHK-2.2), label-accuracy problem. NOT a graded remedy and NOT a
// recommendation to take melatonin: it's context on why the number on a gummy label is unreliable.
// No tier badge, no evidence-gate chips. Every specific is cited to a source verified firsthand:
// Cohen 2023 JAMA (25 gummies, 88% mislabelled, 74–347% of label, undeclared CBD — read from PMC),
// Erland 2017 (30 supplements, 83% below to 478% above label; 465% lot-to-lot; serotonin in 8),
// Lelak 2022 MMWR (pediatric ingestions rose 530%). Mirrors melatonin-children.astro exactly.
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import ContextBanner from '../components/ContextBanner.astro';
import ContextSources from '../components/ContextSources.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../components/Disclaimer.astro';
import Fn from '../components/Fn.astro';

const sources = [
  {
    n: 1,
    cite: 'Cohen PA, Avula B, Wang YH, Katragunta K, Khan I. Quantity of Melatonin and CBD in Melatonin Gummies Sold in the US. JAMA. 2023;329(16):1401–1402.',
    finding:
      'independent analysis of 25 melatonin gummy products sold in the US: 22 of 25 (88%) were inaccurately labelled, actual melatonin ranged from 74% to 347% of the labelled amount, five products declared CBD (measured 10.6–31.3 mg per serving), and one product contained no detectable melatonin at all — only 31.3 mg of CBD.',
    pmid: '37097362',
  },
  {
    n: 2,
    cite: 'Erland LAE, Saxena PK. Melatonin Natural Health Products and Supplements: Presence of Serotonin and Significant Variability of Melatonin Content. J Clin Sleep Med. 2017;13(2):275–281.',
    finding:
      'lab analysis of 30 supplements: actual melatonin content ranged from 83% below to 478% above the label, varied up to 465% between lots of the same product, and serotonin was detected in eight products — so the number on the label is not a reliable dose.',
    pmid: '27855744',
    doi: '10.5664/jcsm.6462',
  },
  {
    n: 3,
    cite: 'Lelak K, Vohra V, Neuman MI, et al. Pediatric Melatonin Ingestions — United States, 2012–2021. MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep. 2022;71(22):725–729.',
    finding:
      'reported pediatric melatonin ingestions rose 530% over the decade, the large majority unintentional in young children, with a rise in hospitalisations — the basis for treating melatonin as a medicine to lock away, not a sweet.',
    pmid: '35653284',
    doi: '10.15585/mmwr.mm7122a1',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="melatonin gummies: does the label match the dose? | Somnary"
  description="melatonin gummies are the most popular form and the least reliable: independent lab testing keeps finding the amount in the gummy doesn't match the label, sometimes far more, sometimes none, sometimes undeclared CBD. context on the label-accuracy problem — not a grade."
  canonical="https://somnary.vercel.app/melatonin-gummies"
>
  <main class="page">
    <header class="head">
      <p class="eyebrow">context · label accuracy</p>
      <h1 class="title">Melatonin gummies</h1>
      <p class="dek">
        Gummies are the most popular way to take melatonin and the least reliable. Independent lab
        testing keeps finding that the amount in the gummy doesn't match the amount on the label —
        sometimes far more, occasionally none at all, and sometimes an ingredient that isn't listed.
        This page is context on that label-accuracy problem: not a grade, and not a recommendation to
        take melatonin.
      </p>
    </header>

    <ContextBanner
      note="how much melatonin is actually in a gummy is a manufacturing-quality question, not a settled dose. this page explains what testing has found, and why it's a reason for caution."
    />

    <p class="who">
      <span class="who-tag">who this is for</span>
      anyone choosing, or already using, a melatonin gummy — especially for a child — who assumes the
      number on the label is the dose in the bottle.
    </p>

    <!-- safety boundary: a candy-shaped, unpredictable medicine (serious) -->
    <section class="callout sev-serious" role="note" aria-label="gummy dosing hazard">
      <div class="callout-head">
        <span class="sigil" aria-hidden="true">!</span>
        <p class="callout-title">A gummy that looks like candy is still an unpredictable medicine</p>
      </div>
      <p class="callout-body">
        Because gummies are flavoured and shaped like sweets, they're easy for a child to reach and
        overtake — reported pediatric melatonin ingestions <strong>rose 530%</strong> between 2012 and
        2021 in the United States.<Fn n={3} /> Combined with measured doses that can run
        <strong>several times higher than the label</strong>,<Fn n={1} /> that is a real hazard. Keep
        melatonin capped, out of reach, and treat it as a medicine. Giving melatonin to a child is a
        clinician conversation, not a wiki decision.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- section 01: the claim -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 01</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">What people assume</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The everyday assumption is simple: the label tells you the dose. Someone buys a
          &ldquo;1&nbsp;mg&rdquo; or &ldquo;3&nbsp;mg&rdquo; gummy and expects that amount, dose after
          dose, bottle after bottle. The gummy's low, kid-friendly numbers are read as both gentle and
          precise, and the flavoured, chewable form makes it feel more like a treat than a medicine.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 02: what the evidence shows -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 02</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">What the testing actually found</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          An independent analysis published in <em>JAMA</em> in 2023 measured 25 melatonin gummy
          products sold in the US. <strong>22 of 25 (88%)</strong> were inaccurately labelled, and the
          actual melatonin ranged from <strong>74% to 347% of the labelled amount</strong>. Five
          products declared CBD, measured at 10.6 to 31.3&nbsp;mg per serving; one product contained
          <strong>no detectable melatonin at all</strong> — only 31.3&nbsp;mg of CBD.<Fn n={1} /> This
          isn't unique to gummies. A broader lab analysis of 30 melatonin supplements found content
          from <strong>83% below to 478% above</strong> the label, varying by up to
          <strong>465% between lots</strong> of the same product, with serotonin detected in
          eight.<Fn n={2} />
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 03: what it does NOT show -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 03</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">What these numbers do <em>not</em> tell you</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          These studies measured what is <em>in</em> the products, not what happens to a person who
          takes them. They don't establish a safe dose, a harm threshold, or that any particular brand
          is reliable. A single test also can't promise the next bottle, or the next lot, will measure
          the same — lot-to-lot variation was itself large.<Fn n={2} /> &ldquo;88%
          mislabelled&rdquo; is a quality-control finding about a market, not a verdict on the one
          gummy in your hand. The honest takeaway is narrower and more useful: the printed milligram is
          not something you can rely on.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 04: dose / form / label reality -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 04</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Dose &amp; label reality</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          A gummy gives you the least control over dose of any form. You can't split it accurately, the
          printed number may be off by multiples, and an undeclared ingredient such as CBD may be
          present.<Fn n={1} /> If melatonin is used at all, third-party verification (USP&nbsp;Verified
          or NSF) is the only signal that the contents were independently checked against the label —
          and even that is a manufacturing check, not medical advice. Which form and which dose make
          sense is a conversation for a pharmacist or clinician, not something a label can answer.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 05: take to your clinician -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 05</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Take these to a clinician or pharmacist</h2>
      <ul class="ask">
        <li>is melatonin appropriate for me, or for my child, at all — given age, health, and any other medicines?</li>
        <li>if so, what form and what studied dose range is reasonable, and is a gummy a sensible way to take it?</li>
        <li>how would I choose a product whose contents have been independently verified against the label?</li>
        <li>what should I watch for if a dose turns out to be much higher than the label suggested?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- related: back to the graded hub + the child-safety boundary -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">related</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Read next</h2>
      <ul class="related">
        <li><a href="/r/melatonin">melatonin</a> — the full evidence grade and what the trials found.</li>
        <li><a href="/melatonin-dose-timing">melatonin dose &amp; timing</a> — how much, and when, the studies actually used.</li>
        <li><a href="/melatonin-children">melatonin in children</a> — the safety context behind the gummy-and-kids problem.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <ContextSources sources={sources} />

    <div class="disclaimer-slot">
      <Disclaimer variant="standard" />
    </div>

    <p class="review-line">
      reviewed 2026-07-07 · found an error? <a href="/methodology#corrections">corrections →</a>
    </p>
  </main>
</Base>

